<body>

<header>
<h1>Statistics Learning Website</h1>
<h2>Chapter 6: Diagrammatic Representation</h2>
</header>

<div class="container">

<h2>6.1 Introduction</h2>

<p>
Statistical results can be presented effectively using diagrams and graphs. 
A single diagram can represent data more clearly than many words. Even people 
who are not familiar with numerical data can easily understand diagrams.
</p>

<p>
Diagrams are geometrical figures such as lines, bars, rectangles, circles, 
pictures and maps used to visually represent statistical data.
</p>

<p>
Diagrammatic representation highlights relationships and important facts 
in the data and helps save time and effort in understanding large datasets.
</p>

---

<h2>6.2 Advantages of Diagrams</h2>

<ul>

<li>They are attractive and impressive.</li>
<li>They simplify complex data.</li>
<li>They help in easy comparison.</li>
<li>They save time and labour.</li>
<li>They have universal utility.</li>
<li>They provide more information visually.</li>
<li>They have strong memorizing effect.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>6.3 Demerits / Limitations</h2>

<ul>

<li>They provide only approximate values.</li>
<li>Small differences may not be visible clearly.</li>
<li>Large differences may distort the appearance.</li>
<li>Some diagrams require expert skills.</li>
<li>Different scales may mislead viewers.</li>
<li>Similar data characteristics are needed for comparison.</li>
<li>Limited use for advanced statistical analysis.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>6.4 Types of Diagrams</h2>

<p>Diagrams can be classified into the following categories:</p>

<ul>

<li>One-Dimensional Diagrams</li>
<li>Two-Dimensional Diagrams</li>
<li>Three-Dimensional Diagrams</li>
<li>Pictograms and Cartograms</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>6.5 One-Dimensional Diagrams</h2>

<p>
In these diagrams only length or height is considered while width is ignored.
They are commonly represented using bars or lines.
</p>

<h3>Types</h3>

<ul>

<li>Line Diagram</li>
<li>Simple Bar Diagram</li>
<li>Sub-divided Bar Diagram</li>
<li>Percentage Bar Diagram</li>
<li>Multiple Bar Diagram</li>

</ul>

---

<h3>Line Diagram</h3>

<p>
A line diagram is used when many items need to be shown with small differences.
Vertical lines are drawn based on scale.
</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Example: Number of Children</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th>No. of Children</th>
<th>0</th>
<th>1</th>
<th>2</th>
<th>3</th>
<th>4</th>
<th>5</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Frequency</th>
<td>10</td>
<td>14</td>
<td>9</td>
<td>6</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>2</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h3>Simple Bar Diagram</h3>

<p>
Simple bar diagrams compare values of a single variable for different categories.
Bars may be vertical or horizontal and their heights represent magnitude.
</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Example: Population in States (million)</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Year</th>
<th>UP</th>
<th>AP</th>
<th>MH</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>1951</td>
<td>63.22</td>
<td>31.25</td>
<td>29.98</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h3>Sub-divided Bar Diagram</h3>

<p>
In a sub-divided bar diagram the total bar is divided into parts representing 
different components of the total.
</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Example: Family Expenditure</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Item</th>
<th>Family A (Rs)</th>
<th>Family B (Rs)</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Food</td>
<td>1400</td>
<td>2400</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>House Rent</td>
<td>1600</td>
<td>2600</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Education</td>
<td>1200</td>
<td>1600</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Savings</td>
<td>800</td>
<td>1400</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Total</th>
<th>5000</th>
<th>8000</th>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h3>Percentage Bar Diagram</h3>

<p>
Each bar represents 100% and components are shown as percentages of the total.
</p>

<p><b>Formula:</b></p>

<p>
Percentage = (Actual Value / Total Value) × 100
</p>

---

<h3>Multiple Bar Diagram</h3>

<p>
Multiple bar diagrams compare two or more related sets of data.
Bars are placed side by side for easy comparison.
</p>

---

<h2>6.6 Two-Dimensional Diagrams</h2>

<p>
These diagrams represent data using area. Both length and width are used.
</p>

<h3>Types</h3>

<ul>

<li>Rectangle Diagram</li>
<li>Square Diagram</li>
<li>Circle Diagram</li>
<li>Pie Diagram</li>

</ul>

---

<h3>Pie Diagram</h3>

<p>
Pie diagrams represent total values as a circle divided into sectors representing components.
</p>

<p><b>Formula for Angle:</b></p>

<p>
Angle = (Component Value / Total Value) × 360°
</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Example: Cropping Pattern in Karnataka</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Crop</th>
<th>Area (ha)</th>
<th>Angle</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Cereals</td>
<td>3940</td>
<td>214°</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Oil Seeds</td>
<td>1165</td>
<td>63°</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Pulses</td>
<td>464</td>
<td>25°</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Cotton</td>
<td>249</td>
<td>13°</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Others</td>
<td>822</td>
<td>45°</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Total</th>
<th>6640</th>
<th>360°</th>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h2>6.7 Three-Dimensional Diagrams</h2>

<p>
These diagrams represent data using volume and include length, width and height.
Examples include:
</p>

<ul>

<li>Cubes</li>
<li>Cylinders</li>
<li>Spheres</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>6.8 Pictogram and Cartogram</h2>

<h3>Pictogram</h3>

<p>
A pictogram represents data using pictures or symbols proportional to the data values.
</p>

<h3>Cartogram</h3>

<p>
Cartograms present statistical data on maps using colors, symbols or patterns.
They are commonly used to represent geographical data such as population, production,
birth rates and trade statistics.
</p>

</div>

